04413nam a2200637Ia 9781501732072DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20181995nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017320727 a10.7591/97815017320722doi  a(DE-B1597)514989  a(OCoLC)1088930308  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aBIO0260002bisacsh04a9732201 aOtter, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistory of My Own Times; or, the Life and Adventures of William Otter, Sen., Comprising a Series of Events, and Musical Incidents Altogether Original /cWilliam Otter; ed. by Richard B. Stott. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (256 p.) :bHistory of my own times  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDocuments in American Social History00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPreface -- tEngland -- tNew York -- tPhiladelphia -- tPennsylvania -- tHanover -- tCincinnati, the Eastern Shore, and Baltimore -- tEmmitsburg -- tPOSTSCRIPT -- tCommentary: William Otter and the Society of Jolly Fellows in the Early Republic -- tAppendix: Articles of an Agreement between Rev. John DuBois & William Otter, 11 October 1823 -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBig Bill Otter was one member of the early American working class not preoccupied with republican principles or the heritage of the Revolution. Big Bill Otter—apprentice, journeyman, master plasterer—was a thug.Otter's autobiography, first published in 1835, provides a rare and fascinating counterpoint to romantic notions of virtuous, respectable craftsmen in the early republic. His Life and Adventures offer an inside account of the brawling racism common in the early nineteenth century and sharply detail the rowdy male subculture of the times.Born in England and conscripted into the British Navy during the Napoleonic wars, Otter jumped ship and came to New York City in 1801. He apprenticed as a plasterer and joined an urban gang; later he was a master plasterer, tavernkeeper, slavecatcher, "Jackson man," bigot, town bully, notorious practical joker, borderline psychopath, mayoral candidate, and all-round "jolly fellow."History of My Own Times is one of the few first-person accounts of a rural artisan in pre-genteel America. The book depicts the ambiguities of race relations in the early nineteenth century, sheds light on its definition of manhood, and conveys a sense of humor very different from today's. Richard B. Stott's introduction an,d commentary place Otter in the context of his times and explore the significance of his autobiography in understanding the social and cultural history of the early American republic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArtisanszUnited StatesvBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aU.S. History. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh1 aStott, Richard B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173207240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501732072423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501732072/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles